</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc" />
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Examples">Examples</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Function_composition&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Examples"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Example_for_a_composition_of_two_functions.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Example_for_a_composition_of_two_functions.svg/250px-Example_for_a_composition_of_two_functions.svg.png" decoding="async" width="250" height="301" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Example_for_a_composition_of_two_functions.svg/500px-Example_for_a_composition_of_two_functions.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="450" data-file-height="541" /></a><figcaption>Concrete example for the composition of two functions.</figcaption></figure>
<ul><li>Composition of functions on a finite <a href="/wiki/Set_(mathematics)" title="Set (mathematics)">set</a>: If <span class="texhtml"><i>f</i> = {(1, 1), (2, 3), (3, 1), (4, 2)}</span>, and <span class="texhtml"><i>g</i> = {(1, 2), (2, 3), (3, 1), (4, 2)}</span>, then <span class="texhtml"><i>g</i> ∘ <i>f</i> = {(1, 2), (2, 1), (3, 2), (4, 3)}</span>, as shown in the figure.</li>
<li>Composition of functions on an <a href="/wiki/Infinite_set" title="Infinite set">infinite set</a>: If <span class="texhtml"><i>f</i>: <b>R</b> → <b>R</b></span> (where <span class="texhtml"><b>R</b></span> is the set of all <a href="/wiki/Real_number" title="Real number">real numbers</a>) is given by <span class="texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) = 2<i>x</i> + 4</span> and <span class="texhtml"><i>g</i>: <b>R</b> → <b>R</b></span> is given by <span class="texhtml"><i>g</i>(<i>x</i>) = <i>x</i><sup>3</sup></span>, then: <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r996643573">.mw-parser-output .block-indent{padding-left:3em;padding-right:0;overflow:hidden}</style><div class="block-indent"><span class="texhtml">(<i>f</i> ∘ <i>g</i>)(<i>x</i>) = <i>f</i>(<i>g</i>(<i>x</i>)) = <i>f</i>(<i>x</i><sup>3</sup>) = 2<i>x</i><sup>3</sup> + 4</span>, and</div> <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r996643573" /><div class="block-indent"><span class="texhtml">(<i>g</i> ∘ <i>f</i>)(<i>x</i>) = <i>g</i>(<i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)) = <i>g</i>(2<i>x</i> + 4) = (2<i>x</i> + 4)<sup>3</sup></span>.</div></li>
<li>If an airplane's altitude at time&#160;<span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">t</span> is <span class="texhtml"><i>a</i>(<i>t</i>)</span>, and the air pressure at altitude <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">x</span> is <span class="texhtml"><i>p</i>(<i>x</i>)</span>, then <span class="texhtml">(<i>p</i> ∘ <i>a</i>)(<i>t</i>)</span> is the pressure around the plane at time&#160;<span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">t</span>.</li>
<li>Function defined on finite sets which change the order of their elements such as <a href="/wiki/Permutation" title="Permutation">permutations</a> can be composed on the same set, this being composition of permutations.</li></ul>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Properties">Properties</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Function_composition&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Properties"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The composition of functions is always <a href="/wiki/Associative" class="mw-redirect" title="Associative">associative</a>—a property inherited from the <a href="/wiki/Composition_of_relations" title="Composition of relations">composition of relations</a>.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-Velleman&#95;2006&#95;2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Velleman_2006-2"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>2<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> That is, if <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">f</span>, <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">g</span>, and <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">h</span> are composable, then <span class="texhtml"><i>f</i> ∘ (<i>g</i> ∘ <i>h</i>) = (<i>f</i> ∘ <i>g</i>) ∘ <i>h</i></span>.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-:0&#95;3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-3"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>3<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Since the parentheses do not change the result, they are generally omitted.
</p><p>In a strict sense, the composition <span class="texhtml"><i>g</i> ∘ <i>f</i></span> is only meaningful if the codomain of <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">f</span> equals the domain of <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">g</span>; in a wider sense, it is sufficient that the former be an improper <a href="/wiki/Subset" title="Subset">subset</a> of the latter.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-NB&#95;Strict&#95;4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NB_Strict-4"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>nb 1<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
Moreover, it is often convenient to tacitly restrict the domain of <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">f</span>, such that <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">f</span> produces only values in the domain of <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">g</span>. For example, the composition <span class="texhtml"><i>g</i> ∘ <i>f</i></span> of the functions <span class="texhtml"><i>f</i> : <a href="/wiki/Real_number" title="Real number"><b>R</b></a> → <a href="/wiki/Interval_(mathematics)#Infinite_endpoints" title="Interval (mathematics)">(−∞,+9] </a></span> defined by <span class="texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) = 9 − <i>x</i><sup>2</sup></span> and <span class="texhtml"><i>g</i> : <a href="/wiki/Interval_(mathematics)#Infinite_endpoints" title="Interval (mathematics)">[0,+∞)</a> → <b>R</b></span> defined by <span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle g(x)={\sqrt {x}}}">
